==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|step-|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|steop-|stēop-|deprived of a relative, step-|pos=prefix|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*steupa-||orphaned, step-}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)teup-||to push, strike}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|step-||step-|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|stiep-||step-|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|stief-||step-|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|steef-||step-|lang=nds}}, German {{term|stief-||step-|lang=nl|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|styv-||step-|lang=sv}}, Icelandic {{term|stjúp-||step-|lang=is}}. Related to Old English {{term/t|ang|stīepan||to deprive, bereave}}.

===Prefix===
{{en-prefix}}

# A prefix used before ''father'', ''mother'', ''brother'', ''sister'', ''son'', ''daughter'', ''child'', and so forth, to indicate that the person being identified is not a [[blood relative]] but is related through the [[marriage]] of a parent.

